Group 1 Project: Amazon Fine Food Reviews¶

Gowri Croos & Mark Jones¶

Dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/snap/amazon-fine-food-reviews¶

Problem Statement: We would like to assess the Amazon Reviews to identify top terms customers are using in their reviews to be able to a) have a better sense of what is most important to customers, and b) if there are any insights to be deduced from the favourable product reviews.¶

- We will use data classification and Natural Language Processing (NLP) to analyze the dataset¶

- We want to understand what the majority of customers are looking for in the products they're purchasing and reviewing¶

- For future products or current product improvements, it will be important to know what makes a favourable / unfavourable prodct¶

# Remove http syntax and line breaks

import re
def clean(s):
    s = re.sub(r'<br */*>', "\n", s)
    s = re.sub(r'<a href=', "", s)
    s = re.sub(r'\"*https*://[^\)]*\"*', "", s)
    s = re.sub(r'-', "", s)
    s = re.sub(r'&#34;', "'", s)
    return str(s)
In [5]:
# Apply the clean code function to the dataframe: 1) to the Text portion of the review, and 2) to the Profile Name

df["selftext_clean"] = ''
for i, row in df.iterrows():
    df.at[i, "selftext_clean"] = clean(row.Text)
    

df["ProfileClean"] = ''
for i, row in df.iterrows():
    df.at[i, "ProfileClean"] = clean(row.ProfileName)

In [9]:
import spacy

nlp = spacy.load('en_core_web_sm')
In [10]:
for i, row in df.iterrows():
    if i % 1000 == 0:  # this will act as a progress tracker, each 1,000 records will be marked as completed when it is printed, e.g. 1,000 rows completed when 1,000 is printed             
        print(i)
    if(row["selftext_clean"] and len(str(row["selftext_clean"])) <500000):
        doc = nlp(str(row["selftext_clean"]))
        adjectives = []
        nouns = []
        propn = []
        verbs = []
        lemmas = []

        for token in doc:
            lemmas.append(token.lemma_)
            if token.pos_ == "ADJ":
                adjectives.append(token.lemma_)
            if token.pos_ == "NOUN":
                nouns.append(token.lemma_)
            if token.pos_ == "PROPN":
                propn.append(token.lemma_)
            if token.pos_ == "VERB":
                verbs.append(token.lemma_)
                
        df.at[i, "selftext_lemma"] = " ".join(lemmas)
        df.at[i, "selftext_nouns"] = " ".join(nouns)
        df.at[i, "selftext_propn"] = " ".join(propn)
        df.at[i, "selftext_adjectives"] = " ".join(adjectives)
        df.at[i, "selftext_verbs"] = " ".join(verbs)
        df.at[i, "selftext_npav"] = " ".join(nouns+propn+adjectives+verbs)
        df.at[i, "no_tokens"] = len(lemmas)

Data Exploration¶

Profile Name Exploration¶

In [12]:
# Taking a look at the top users and their avg ratings

df_u = df.groupby('ProfileName') \
           .agg({'Id': pd.Series.nunique,
                 'HelpfulnessNumerator': pd.Series.sum,
                 'Score': pd.Series.sum,
                 'no_tokens':pd.Series.sum}) \
           .rename(columns={'Id': 'Reviews',
                            'HelpfulnessNumerator': 'Helpful_Score',
                            'Score': 'Rating',
                            'no_tokens': 'Nbr_Tokens'}) \
           .sort_values('Rating', ascending=False)

df_u['Avg_Rating'] = np.where(df_u['Reviews'] < 1, df_u['Reviews'], df_u['Rating']/df_u['Reviews'])
df_u['Avg_Tokens'] = np.where(df_u['Reviews'] < 1, df_u['Reviews'], df_u['Nbr_Tokens']/df_u['Reviews'])

In [28]:
# Creating a multi-boxplot function that we can call.  One of the key features of this is to be able to
    # call a y-limit as we'll show in some of the subsequent steps to visually cut off outliers

def multi_boxplot(data, x, y, ylim= None):
    '''Wrapper for sns boxplot with cut-off functionality'''
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    
    # order boxplots by median
    ordered_values = data.groupby(x)[[y]] \
                        .median() \
                        .sort_values(y, ascending=False) \
                        .index
    
    sns.boxplot(x=x, y=y, data=data, palette='Set2',
               order=ordered_values)
    
    fig.set_size_inches(11,6)
    
    # cut-off y-axis at value ylim
    ax.set_ylim(0, ylim)

# Importing the stop words from the spacy package

from spacy.lang.en.stop_words import STOP_WORDS

# Creating a function to remove the stop words from the list of tokens

def remove_stopwords(tokens):
    """Remove stopwords from a list of tokens."""
    return [t for t in tokens if t not in STOP_WORDS]

# Re-processing the tokens with the new function to remove the stop words.

counter = Counter(remove_stopwords(tokens))

# Based on the counter list, we can create a wordcloud visualization of the top tokens

from wordcloud import WordCloud


# The function to create the wordcloud using, setting some defaults and parameters for the display

def wordcloud(counter):
    """A small wordloud wrapper"""
    wc = WordCloud(width=1200, height=800, 
                   background_color="white", 
                   max_words=200) 
    wc.generate_from_frequencies(counter)

    # Plot
    fig=plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    plt.imshow(wc, interpolation='bilinear')
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.tight_layout(pad=0)
    plt.show()
